title: Romanian WASR2 5.45mm AK74
postcontent:
You are looking at a Romanian WASR2 AK74 that has been customized to have that AK74 look. I have added a Bulgarian AK74 stock/furniture set. I also had the barrel threaded to 14mm LH threads. The Muzzle brake on the end is a true AK74 24MM threaded brake. There is a removable adapter set into the brake that allows it to be used on the 14mm Threads. The brake and adapter are attached via blue thread locker, so it is removable. I have fired less than 500 rounds through the barrel. This Rifle fires the very fast, very accurate 5.45x39mm round that is used in the Russian AK74. This round is very similar to the 5.56mm round and MUCH CHEAPER! One black Bulgarian 30 round magazine will be included (either circle 10 or circle 21, no choice).

title: Antique 12ga double barrel double hammer shotgun
postcontent:
I have a very old 12 ga shotgun up for grabs, I was informed by the NRA several years ago that it is anywhere from 85 to 120 yrs old and that was nearly 10 years ago. It is still fully functional as I have shot it several times, and I do have a couple of reloads for it as well as 2 original Remington peters 00 buck high brass wax paper shells ( unfired ). I think it was an old coach gun but not sure and could really use alot of TLC. I am open to any reasonable and serious offers or trades, as far as trades go I would consider any type of wheel gun or an auto 9mm or larger. I have no idea what the value of this shotgun is, but someone here does. Thank You and have a great day. 

PS I did some research online and came up with the following based on markings on this gun: Neumann Bros. shotguns were made by Neumann Freres, a Belgium gun making company from 1863 to 1957.
The crowned ELG proof means it was made in Belgium after 1893 and was proofed for black powder.
The "Machine Made" part is in English.....so it was a Belgian gun made for the American market.
The "machine made" stamp by itself was used by any of three companies on mass produced shotguns sold through American distributers.
The "Belgium Laminated Steel" on the barrel was the same.

title: Surefire M961XM07 Tactical Weapon Light
postcontent:
SureFire flashlights are known around the world as the lighting system for any and every tactical scenario. In 1969 their original product line consisted of laser sighting systems for firearms. After many years of intense research and development, the SureFire WeaponLight was born and low light law enforcement & military operations changed forever. SureFire then went on to establish themselves as the leading manufacturer of rugged, powerful and compact illumination tools for tactical applications; from weapon-mounted lights and laser sights, shield lights, baton lights & hand-held lights powerful and bright enough to qualify as force-multiplier tools that could temporarily blind, unbalance, and disorient a threat.

The M961XM07 Millennium Universal WeaponLight is designed for Mil-Std 1913 Picatinny rail interface equipped shoulder-fired weapons. The included thumbscrew mount ensures quick attachment or removal during high stress conditions.

This WeaponLight features a shock-isolated modular system and components, for rapid conversions in the field to meet mission-specific requirements. The bezel, lamp, and tail cap are interchangeable with SureFire's Special Operations Series hand-held flashlights.

The Millennium Universal (MU) WeaponLights are designed and constructed to endure and perform under harsh battlefield conditions. They're finished with a durable Mil-Spec hard anodizing (Mil-A-8625 Type III Class 2), and the rugged CNC machined housings are o-ring sealed for moisture and dust protection.

The Millennium Universal M962XM07 WeaponLight is powered by three lithium batteries, and produces a 125 lumen beam. The optional MN11 high-output bulb produces a 225 lumen beam.

. CNC machined aluminum housing is o-ring sealed
. Mil-Spec hard anodized finish is extremely durable
. Thumbscrew mount enables quick installation and removal
. 1.62" Bezel accepts SureFire's accessory filters and protective cover
. Tactical XM07 Tail Cap Switch
The XM07 tail cap switch assembly features a click-on/off push-button switch, a plug in momentary-on switch with a 7.0" cable, and a system disable option. These switches operate independently of each other. When the tail cap switch is activated, the tape switch is disabled. Turning the tail cap switch to the off position activates the tape switch. The system disable feature eliminates the possibility of accidental activation from either switch.
. High Output
Included MN11 bulb produces a powerful 225 lumen beam
. Turbohead Option
Optional beam-focusing 2.5" Turbohead delivers a tighter, longer reaching beam
. Prefocused Beam
No need to twist the bezel to adjust the beam, it's already perfectly prefocused. Lamps and reflectors are individually mated and hand-adjusted to within .005" for optimum beam quality at all distances.
. The SureFire Difference
SureFire strives to design and manufacture lights of ever-increasing brightness and quality while setting new standards for maximum power with minimal size. Three things characterize every product: compact size, extreme ruggedness, and a flawless high-output beam. Every SureFire illumination tool is guaranteed to produce a perfect center spot of intense light surrounded by a smooth corona of softer light.
. No Hassle Lifetime Warranty
Lamps will burn out, batteries will be used up, and switches for WeaponLightsT will eventually need to be replaced. Everything else is covered by their lifetime no-hassle guarantee; if it breaks, SureFire will fix it!
. Made in the USA

title: WWll Military issue Kriegsmarine Mauser HSc for sale
postcontent: This 7.65mm Kal. (.32 cal.) pistol was handed down to me by my uncle who had captured it while in the navy. As far as I know, he had never fired it while using it for protection when he owned a drug store (he preferred his 1903 colt .32 cal. rimmles, smokeless automatic) and I have not fired it since owning it. It has been well kept and in excellent condition but needs a cleaning. I am assuming that 90% of it's use was by the original owner. What makes this pistol special is that it was issued to the Kriegsmarine ( it has all the correct stampings, the eagle over N an the rarest of Kriegsmarine stamps, the M/6 on the trigger guard) which, as you may know, most of these pistols are at the bottom of the Alantic unlike those issued to the army or police. It has a 839xxx serial number which indicates that it was manufactured in 1943. It would make a great addition to any war collection.

From speer-ammo.com:
" We created the first bonded-core handgun bullet. Our method is so innovative that we hold patents* on the process. Using our proven Uni-Cor® technology, we bond the copper jacket to the lead core one molecule at a time. We've virtually wiped out the cause of most bullet failures - core-jacket separation. In the process, we've assured high retained weights and excellent penetration.
What about expansion? We have you covered. Most bullet makers add the hollow point cavity at the very last operation. This is not very smart if you want premium performance. We, however, form the cavity in two distinct steps. Very smart.
The first cavity operation establishes the limit of maximum expansion--a bullet isn't very effective if it rolls back so far that it falls apart--and precuts both the jacket and the core for symmetrical expansion. The final cavity operation establishes the rate of expansion. The flexibility of this two-step proces lets us tune each bullet to its intended velocity range. Bullets for low-velocity cartridges have a deep cavity; those for high-velocity have a shallow cavity. Very smart, indeed.
We put a lot into Gold Dot. Accuracy. Penetration. Incredible terminal performance. Now you can put all that in your handloads.
*US Pat. Off. Reg. No. 5,079,814 and all applicable foreign patents."

title: Cold Steel CS14R1 Military knife
postcontent: This is a new in the box Cold Steel Military R1. Sheath is lighter than it appears in the photo. Now you can own an exact replica of this original classic for a very reasonable price. But make no mistake, our R1 Military Classic is not just a showpiece. The blade is expertly crafted from VG-1 San Mai III® blade construction and is 3/16" thick. Each one is flawlessly ground, hand fitted, polished and then honed until it will cut at the slightest touch. For strength and beauty, the double guard has been meticulously fashioned from a single piece of highly rust resistant 300 series stainless steel (instead of brass or nickel silver that can tarnish). It sports an extremely buffed and polished surface that will continue to gleam despite the ravages of time and weather. The handle is made from solid black linen Micarta. This is extremely costly, but nothing else looks or lasts like Micarta! Each one is contoured and shaped until perfect then permanently mated to the heavy blade tang with attractive colored fiber spacers. The final assembly is then buffed and polished to a fine luster. The R1 is delivered with a heavy duty brown leather sheath complete with Norton Fine India stone and pouch. This rugged sheath is built for hard service and is designed to fit virtually any belt including a G.I. pistol Belt! Military Classic Specifications: Blade: 7" Handle: 4 5/8" Overall: 11 5/8" Thick: 3/16" Weight: 9.25oz. VG-1 San Mai III® Stainless with 300 Series Stainless guards. Black linen Micarta handles. Sharpening Stone included with leather sheath

title: Cold Steel CS18H Outdoorsman knife
postcontent: This is a new in the box Cold Steel Outdoorsman hunting knife.  We have had a lot of friends ask us to bring back the Outdoorsman. So we have dusted off the tooling and made a new run. Only this time we have added two new improvements. The first is jimping on the blade back. This gives the thumb and index finger more control of the edge as they now have a non-slip platform to rest on. The second is a chopping edge, or bone breaker. In our tests, this edge hacked through everything we put in front of it, including heavy gauge steel wire, so it's sure to stand up in the field! As before, the Outdoorsman will come with a heavy leather sheath, fitted with a brush proof retaining strap. Outdoorsman Specifications: Weight: 9.9 oz. title: Antique 12ga double barrel (Neumann Bros)
postcontent:
Antique 12ga double barrel shotgun. It has the external hammers and double triggers. It is shootable as I have done so( you have to use low Pressure loads) anyone that does reloading can make up a batch.The following is some of the info I was able to find about this shotgun.
{Neumann Bros. shotguns were made by Neumann Freres, a Belgium gun making company from 1863 to 1957.
The crowned ELG proof means it was made in Belgium after 1893 and was proofed for black powder.
The "Machine Made" part is in English.....so it was a Belgian gun made for the American market.
The "machine made" stamp by itself was used by any of three companies on mass produced shotguns sold through American distributers.
The "Belgium Laminated Steel" on the barrel was the same.
The writing on the left side plate would be a store brand or maker's name ala "Wm. Parkhurst" or "Wm. Moore & Co" or "Manton and Co." etc etc etc.
The E over the LG in the oval with the crown is a Belgium proof mark that began in 1893 and stands for "definitive black powder proof for breech loading guns, small bore guns and handguns.
I have a couple of shells for it as well including two Remington Peters 00buck High Brass waxed paper shell in mint condition (unfired). It could use alot of tlc  and some stock work.
